const a = [
  {"id":6423,"text":"Where is the micturition reflex center located?","explanation":"The micturition reflex center is located in the **rostral pontine tegmentum**, specifically within the region known as the pontine micturition center (PMC) or Barrington's nucleus. This center integrates signals from the bladder via afferent pathways. When the bladder fills and stretches, stretch receptors in its wall send impulses to the spinal cord and then ascend to the PMC. Once a certain threshold of stretch is reached, the PMC facilitates the micturition reflex, resulting in coordinated bladder contraction and urethral sphincter relaxation, leading to urination. Additionally, higher centers in the brain, especially the cerebral cortex, can inhibit or facilitate the micturition reflex, providing voluntary control over urination. Thus, while the actual reflex is coordinated in the pontine micturition center, voluntary control is exerted from higher cerebral areas.","reference":"(1) Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 328.   \r\n \r\n(2) Sugaya K, Nishijima S, Miyazato M, Ogawa Y. Central nervous control of micturition and urine storage. Journal of Smooth Muscle Research = Nihon Heikatsukin Gakkai Kikanshi. Published June 2005. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16006745/#:~:text=The%20micturition%20reflex%20is%20a,other%20is%20the%20spinothalamic%20tract.","responses":[{"text":"Hypothalamus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rostral pontine tegmentum","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Spinal cord","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medulla oblongata","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cerebellum","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":6677,"text":"Disturbance in the renal reabsorption of bicarbonates in the proximal tubules leads to which one of the following?","explanation":"In the kidneys, bicarbonate (HCO₃⁻) reabsorption in the proximal tubules is a primary mechanism for conserving the body's bicarbonate and thus maintaining the pH of body fluids. Disturbances in the renal reabsorption of bicarbonate in the proximal tubules can lead to its excessive loss in the urine. This loss of bicarbonate decreases the buffering capacity of the blood, resulting in **metabolic acidosis**. Metabolic acidosis is characterized by a decrease in plasma bicarbonate concentration and a decrease in arterial blood pH. Other potential causes of metabolic acidosis include excess acid production (like lactic acidosis) and inability to excrete acid (renal failure). However, when bicarbonate reabsorption is specifically disturbed in the proximal tubules, loss of this essential buffer results in metabolic acidosis.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 415.","responses":[{"text":"Metabolic alkalosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metabolic acidosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypochloremia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acidic urine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nitrogen retention","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":6684,"text":"If plasma colloidal osmotic pressure is 40 mmHg, renal capillary pressure is 60 mmHg, and Bowman's capsule hydrostatic pressure is 18 mmHg, which of the following effect occurs in the kidney?","explanation":"The net filtration pressure (NFP) in the glomerulus is determined by the balance between forces promoting filtration (renal capillary pressure) and those opposing filtration (plasma colloidal osmotic pressure and Bowman's capsule hydrostatic pressure). \r\n\r\nNFP = Renal capillary pressure - (Plasma colloidal osmotic pressure + Bowman's capsule hydrostatic pressure)\r\nNFP = 60 mmHg - (40 mmHg + 18 mmHg) = 2 mmHg\r\n\r\nTypically, a positive NFP is required for glomerular filtration to occur. Given the provided pressures, the NFP is reduced to only 2 mmHg. A decreased NFP translates to a **reduced glomerular filtration rate (GFR)**. This means less plasma is filtered through the glomeruli, reducing the volume of filtrate produced and eventually reducing urine output.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 334.","responses":[{"text":"Glomerular filtration rate (GFR) is reduced","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Afferent arteriolar dilatation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Contraction of macula densa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glomerular filtration rate (GFR) is increased","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Efferent arteriolar dilatation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":6757,"text":"Which of the following provides arterial supply to the pelvic part of the ureter?","explanation":"The **ureter** receives its blood supply from a variety of sources throughout its course due to its descending nature. For the pelvic part of the ureter, the primary source of blood supply is from branches of the **internal iliac artery**. Specifically, the **superior vesical artery**, a branch of the anterior trunk of the internal iliac artery, provides blood to the superior aspect of the bladder and the distal parts of the ureter.","reference":"Drake RL, Vogl W, Mitchell AWM, Gray H. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 3rd ed. Churchill Livingstone/Elsevier; 2015: 496.","responses":[{"text":"Gonadal artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior vesical artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Abdominal aorta","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Internal iliac artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":6763,"text":"The examination of a cross-section of kidneys shows the renal columns of Bertin. Which statement best defines the renal columns of Bertin?","explanation":"The **renal columns of Bertin** are extensions of the renal cortex that project inward, intervening between the renal pyramids in the medulla of the kidney. They serve as a distinguishing feature when examining the internal structure of the kidney, particularly in a cross-sectional view. These columns essentially represent cortical tissue that dips into the medulla, dividing the medullary region into a series of triangular-shaped renal pyramids. The renal columns are mainly composed of the same tissue found in the renal cortex, including blood vessels and renal tubules, but they lack the glomeruli which are confined to the cortex.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2018: 393.","responses":[{"text":"Medullary substance that extends into cortex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cortical substance that extends into medulla","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Nephrons that are drained by a common collecting duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Convoluted parts of renal tubules","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Marks beginning of nephron","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":6802,"text":"Which of the following is not the part of renal filtration barrier?","explanation":"The renal filtration barrier, crucial for selectively filtering blood, comprises three main components:\r\n\r\n1. **Fenestrated endothelium of glomerular capillaries:** These fenestrations allow easy passage of water, ions, and small molecules but block blood cells and larger proteins.\r\n \r\n2. **Basal lamina (or basement membrane):** A meshwork of glycoproteins and proteoglycans, it serves as a secondary filter, especially for negatively charged molecules.\r\n\r\n3. **Podocytes:** These cells have foot processes called pedicels, which interdigitate with one another, forming filtration slits that are covered by the slit diaphragm, a unique structure that further restricts the passage of large molecules.\r\n\r\nThe **continuous epithelium of glomerular capillaries** is not a component of the filtration barrier. The endothelium of glomerular capillaries is fenestrated, not continuous.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2018: 389.","responses":[{"text":"Basal lamina","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Continuous epithelium of glomerular capillaries","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fenestrated endothelium of glomerular capillaries","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endothelial cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Podocytes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9368,"text":"What may the kidneys enhance in response to acidosis?","explanation":"Acidosis indicates an accumulation of H⁺ ions in the body, leading to a decreased blood pH. In response to acidosis, the kidneys play a pivotal role in restoring acid-base balance by:\r\n\r\n1. **Enhancing the secretion of H⁺ ions:** The primary response to acidosis is an increased secretion of hydrogen ions (H⁺) in the renal tubules, allowing their elimination in urine. This helps in reducing the overall H⁺ concentration in the blood.\r\n\r\n2. **Reabsorbing bicarbonate (HCO₃⁻) ions:** As H⁺ ions are secreted, HCO₃⁻ ions are simultaneously reabsorbed into the blood from the renal tubules. This bicarbonate reabsorption aids in buffering the excess H⁺ ions, further helping to restore the acid-base balance.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 410.","responses":[{"text":"Secretion of HCO₃⁻","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secretion of K⁺ ions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urea retention","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secretion of H⁺ ions","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Secretion of Na⁺ ions","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12105,"text":"Allopurinol is a structural analog of which of the following compounds?","explanation":"Allopurinol is primarily used as a treatment for gout and is known to inhibit the enzyme xanthine oxidase. This enzyme is responsible for the oxidation of hypoxanthine to xanthine and subsequently the oxidation of xanthine to uric acid. By inhibiting xanthine oxidase, allopurinol prevents the formation of uric acid, thereby reducing its levels in the blood.\r\n\r\nAllopurinol's ability to inhibit xanthine oxidase is due to its structural similarity to the natural substrate of the enzyme, **hypoxanthine**. As a structural analog of hypoxanthine, allopurinol can bind to xanthine oxidase, acting as a competitive inhibitor. This leads to decreased uric acid production, which is beneficial in conditions like gout, where there's an overproduction or under-excretion of uric acid.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 301.","responses":[{"text":"Hypoxanthine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Phosphoribosyl pyrophosphate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inosine monophosphate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Uric acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Xanthine oxidase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12106,"text":"What is the osmolarity of the glomerular filtrate that enters the proximal convoluted tubule?","explanation":"The glomerular filtrate is essentially plasma without proteins. As it's filtered from the glomerulus into Bowman's capsule, its osmolarity is approximately the same as that of plasma. The normal osmolarity of plasma is around **300 mOsm/L**. Thus, the osmolarity of the glomerular filtrate that enters the proximal convoluted tubule is also 300 mOsm/L. As the filtrate travels through the various segments of the nephron, its osmolarity will change due to reabsorption and secretion of solutes and water. For instance, in the descending loop of Henle, water is reabsorbed making the filtrate more concentrated, while in the thick ascending limb, solutes are reabsorbed without water, making the filtrate more dilute. However, at the very beginning, in the proximal tubule, it maintains the osmolarity of plasma.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 366.","responses":[{"text":"400 mOsm/L","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"100 mOsm/L","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"200 mOsm/L","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"300 mOsm/L","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"1200 mOsm/L","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12114,"text":"Increased secretion of aldosterone leads to which of the following?","explanation":"Aldosterone is a hormone secreted by the adrenal cortex that acts primarily on the renal collecting tubules. Its primary effects are to promote sodium reabsorption and potassium secretion. Along with this, aldosterone promotes the secretion of hydrogen ions (H⁺) into the urine. As a result:\r\n\r\n1. **Increased Sodium Reabsorption**: This helps in retaining sodium in the body, potentially leading to an expanded extracellular fluid volume but does not lead to hypernatremia unless there's an inadequate water intake or ADH response.\r\n   \r\n2. **Increased Potassium Secretion**: This can lead to a lowered blood potassium level, or hypokalemia.\r\n   \r\n3. **Increased Hydrogen Ion Secretion**: The increased secretion of H⁺ ions can cause the blood to become more alkaline, resulting in metabolic alkalosis.\r\n\r\nTherefore, increased secretion of aldosterone can lead to metabolic alkalosis, among other potential disturbances.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 398, 960.","responses":[{"text":"Hyponatremia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metabolic acidosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperkalemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metabolic alkalosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypernatremia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12229,"text":"A female comes into the clinic with oral ulcers, hematuria, and +1 proteinuria. 1-2 white blood cells/HPF are found on urinalysis. What is the most probable diagnosis?","explanation":"The clinical presentation of oral ulcers combined with hematuria and proteinuria is suggestive of systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE), a multisystem autoimmune disease. When SLE affects the kidneys, it is referred to as lupus nephritis.\r\n\r\n1. **Oral ulcers** are one of the common mucocutaneous manifestations of SLE.\r\n   \r\n2. **Hematuria and Proteinuria**: These are signs of kidney involvement, and lupus nephritis can manifest with a variety of renal syndromes, ranging from mild hematuria or proteinuria to rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis.\r\n\r\n3. **White Blood Cells in Urine**: The presence of white blood cells in the urine can indicate an inflammatory process in the kidneys.\r\n\r\nWhile other options listed can cause hematuria and proteinuria, the combination of oral ulcers and the described urinalysis findings make lupus nephritis the most probable diagnosis in this context.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 480.","responses":[{"text":"Lupus nephritis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Glomerulonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acid excretion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Membranous nephropathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgA nephropathy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12247,"text":"Which of the following is the narrowest part of the ureter, well above the urinary bladder, where stones can get lodged?","explanation":"The ureter has several anatomically narrow points where kidney stones (calculi) are more likely to get lodged. These narrow points include:\r\n\r\n1. The **ureteropelvic junction** (where the renal pelvis transitions to the ureter).\r\n2. The crossing at the **pelvic brim** (also known as the iliac vessels or pelvic inlet).\r\n3. The **ureterovesical junction** (where the ureter enters the bladder).\r\n\r\nOf the options provided, the **pelvic brim** represents the narrow constriction well above the urinary bladder where stones can get lodged. The pelvic brim is the site where the ureter crosses over the bifurcation of the common iliac artery or the beginning of the external iliac artery.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 526.","responses":[{"text":"Bladder wall","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Major calyx","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pelvicalyceal junction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pelvic brim","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Minor calyx","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13004,"text":"Which of the following is the correct order of the coverings of the kidneys from outwards to inwards?","explanation":"The kidneys are retroperitoneal organs, meaning they are located posterior to the peritoneum. From the outermost layer to the innermost:\r\n\r\n1. **Paranephric fat (or perirenal fat)**: This is the outermost adipose tissue that surrounds the kidneys but is external to the renal fascia.\r\n  \r\n2. **Renal fascia (or Gerota’s fascia)**: A layer of connective tissue that envelops the kidneys and the perinephric fat, providing an anchoring sheath.\r\n\r\n3. **Perinephric fat**: An immediate layer of adipose tissue that directly surrounds the renal capsule and is contained within the renal fascia.\r\n\r\n4. **Renal capsule**: The innermost tough fibrous layer that tightly adheres to the kidney's surface, offering protection from trauma and infection.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 515.","responses":[{"text":"Renal fascia - Perinephric fat - Paranephric fat - Renal capsule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal capsule - Renal fascia - Perinephric fat - Paranephric fat","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Perinephric fat - Renal fascia - Paranephric fat - Renal capsule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal capsule - Paranephric fat - Perinephric fat - Renal fascia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Paranephric fat - Renal fascia - Perinephric fat - Renal capsule","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13006,"text":"Which of the following arteries is responsible for the arterial supply to the proximal part of the ureter?","explanation":"The ureter receives its blood supply from multiple sources along its length due to its course from the kidney to the bladder. The **proximal part of the ureter** (closest to the kidney) is primarily supplied by the **renal artery**. As the ureter courses downward, it will receive branches from other arteries, including the gonadal (testicular or ovarian) artery, common iliac artery, and internal iliac artery, among others, depending on its segmental location. But for the initial or proximal segment, which is the closest to the kidney, the renal artery plays the key role in its vascularization.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 520.","responses":[{"text":"Common iliac","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gonadal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Suprarenal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cystic","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13008,"text":"A 6-year-old female is brought to the urology clinic with the complaint of urinary incontinence. Further investigation revealed that the urine was not coming from the bladder, but was continuously dribbling from the vagina. What is the most appropriate diagnosis for this patient?","explanation":"An **ectopic ureter** is a congenital anomaly where one or both ureters don't open into the bladder but instead have an abnormal termination. In females, an ectopic ureter can often terminate in the urethra, vagina, or, rarely, the uterus. If the ureter opens into the vagina, as suggested in the clinical scenario, it can lead to continuous dribbling of urine independent of normal urination. This continuous leakage is due to the fact that the urine bypasses the bladder and has no storage mechanism before being excreted. It's important to distinguish this from urinary incontinence, where the problem lies in bladder control. An ectopic ureter may be associated with a duplicated collecting system or can be a singular anomaly. Early diagnosis and surgical intervention can often correct the abnormality.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 250.","responses":[{"text":"Ectopic bladder","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ectopic kidney","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Supernumerary kidney","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Autosomal recessive polycystic kidney disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ectopic ureter","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13009,"text":"Microscopically the Bowman's capsule comprises an inner visceral layer and an outer parietal layer. Cells lining the visceral layer have a star-shaped body with primary and secondary processes. Which of the following cells best fits this description?","explanation":"The Bowman's capsule surrounds the glomerulus in the renal corpuscle and consists of two layers: the inner visceral layer and the outer parietal layer. The cells lining the visceral layer have a distinct morphology characterized by a star-shaped body with primary and secondary foot processes. These cells are termed **podocytes**. The foot processes of the podocytes wrap around the glomerular capillaries and interdigitate with foot processes from adjacent podocytes, leaving filtration slits between them. Podocytes play a critical role in the filtration barrier, preventing the passage of large proteins from the bloodstream into the urinary space. The parietal layer, in contrast, is composed of simple squamous epithelial cells and does not participate directly in filtration.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2018: 397.","responses":[{"text":"Mesangial cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Brush cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Podocytes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Simple cuboidal cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endothelial cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13010,"text":"Which part of the urogenital sinus gives rise to the urethra in females?","explanation":"In females, the urogenital sinus undergoes differentiation to give rise to several structures of the reproductive and urinary systems. Specifically, the urogenital sinus can be divided into three parts: the upper vesical part, the middle pelvic part, and the lower phallic part. \r\n\r\nIn females, the **pelvic part of the urogenital sinus** primarily gives rise to the urethra. The vesical part is more involved with the formation of the urinary bladder, while the phallic part contributes to the formation of external genital structures.","reference":"Libretti S, Aeddula NR. Embryology, genitourinary. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed December 6, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK559309/","responses":[{"text":"Widest part of the urogenital sinus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tip of the urogenital sinus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phallic part of the urogenital sinus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pelvic part of the urogenital sinus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vesical part of the urogenital sinus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13018,"text":"In a healthy individual, what percentage of renal plasma flow would you expect to be passed into the glomerular capsule?","explanation":"In a healthy individual, the fraction of renal plasma flow that passes into the glomerular capsule is known as the glomerular filtration rate (GFR). The GFR reflects the proportion of plasma that is filtered as it passes through the glomeruli. Normally, about **15 to 20%** of the renal plasma flow is filtered into the Bowman's capsule. The majority of the plasma remains in the glomerular capillaries and does not undergo filtration. This filtered fraction is critical for the kidneys to effectively clear solutes, maintain fluid and electrolyte balance, and excrete metabolic waste products. The remaining unfiltered plasma continues through the efferent arterioles into the peritubular capillaries, where reabsorption and secretion processes further modify the tubular fluid.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 331.","responses":[{"text":"Between 75 and 80%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Greater than 90%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Between 15 and 20%","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Between 45 and 50%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Less than 5%","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13021,"text":"Which of the following structures is most involved in concentrating the urine?","explanation":"Urine concentration primarily occurs in the renal medulla, where a gradient of osmolarity is established. **Juxtamedullary nephrons** play a pivotal role in this process due to their long loops of Henle that extend deep into the medulla. As the filtrate travels down the descending limb of the loop of Henle, water is reabsorbed, making the filtrate increasingly concentrated. Conversely, in the ascending limb, solutes (like Na+ and Cl-) are reabsorbed, making the filtrate more dilute. This countercurrent mechanism in combination with the vasa recta (blood vessels) creates and maintains the osmotic gradient in the medulla, allowing the collecting ducts to reabsorb more water and produce concentrated urine when necessary. Superficial nephrons lack such long loops and do not contribute significantly to urine concentration.","reference":"Costanzo LS. Physiology. 6th ed. Elsevier; 2018: 283.","responses":[{"text":"Superficial nephrons","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glomerulus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bowman's capsule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Juxtamedullary nephron","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Proximal convoluted tubule","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13041,"text":"Which type of transport is exhibited by the Na-K-2Cl transporter in the apical membrane of the thick ascending loop of Henle?","explanation":"The Na-K-2Cl transporter (also known as the NKCC2 transporter) is located in the apical membrane of the thick ascending limb of the loop of Henle. This transporter moves sodium (Na+), potassium (K+), and two chloride (Cl-) ions from the tubular lumen into the cells of the nephron. This movement of ions is energetically driven by the sodium gradient, which is maintained by the primary active transport action of the Na+/K+ ATPase pump located on the basolateral membrane, which actively pumps sodium out of the cell and potassium into the cell. \r\n\r\nBecause the Na-K-2Cl transporter uses the energy stored in the sodium gradient (which is maintained by the primary active transport) to transport these ions, it is an example of **secondary active transport**.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 345, 351.","responses":[{"text":"Facilitated diffusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primary active transport","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Counter transport","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secondary active transport","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Passive transport","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13238,"text":"What is the tonicity of urine as it enters the renal collecting duct?","explanation":"The tonicity of the urine changes as it flows through the various segments of the nephron. As the filtrate traverses the proximal convoluted tubule (PCT) and the descending loop of Henle, water is reabsorbed, making the filtrate isotonic. As it proceeds into the ascending loop of Henle, the thick segment actively transports solutes out (like Na+, K+, and Cl-) without significant water reabsorption, which renders the filtrate hypotonic by the time it exits the loop.\r\n\r\nBy the time urine reaches the distal convoluted tubule (DCT) and early collecting duct, it is hypotonic compared to the plasma. Hence, as urine enters the collecting duct, it is typically hypotonic. However, further water reabsorption in the collecting duct, especially under the influence of antidiuretic hormone (ADH), can modulate the final tonicity of the urine that is excreted.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 366.","responses":[{"text":"Hypotonic or isotonic, but never hypertonic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypotonic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertonic or isotonic, but never hypotonic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Isotonic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertonic","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13241,"text":"All of the glucose is absorbed by the proximal convoluted tubule. Approximately 90% is in the first part of the proximal convoluted tubule. Which of the following transporters is responsible for transporting the major amount of glucose from the tubular lumen into the cell?","explanation":"The proximal convoluted tubule (PCT) of the nephron plays a critical role in the reabsorption of filtered glucose from the renal tubular lumen back into the bloodstream. There are two main sodium-glucose cotransporters (SGLTs) involved in this process: SGLT1 and SGLT2.\r\n\r\nSGLT2 is located primarily in the early part (S1 segment) of the PCT and is responsible for approximately 90% of glucose reabsorption. Since the early part of the PCT reabsorbs the majority of the filtered glucose, SGLT2 plays a dominant role in this process.\r\n\r\nSGLT1, on the other hand, is found in the latter part (S3 segment) of the PCT and accounts for the remaining 10% of glucose reabsorption.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 345.","responses":[{"text":"SGLT 2","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"GLUT 2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"GLUT 4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"SGLT 1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"GLUT 1","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13243,"text":"A substance \"X\" has the following properties:\r\nUrinary concentration (U) = 0 mg/ml Plasma concentration (P) = 13.6 mg/ml.\r\nIf a patient has a urinary flow rate (V) of 2 ml/min, what is the renal clearance rate of X?","explanation":"The renal clearance rate (C) of a substance is calculated using the formula:\r\nC = (U x V) / P\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n- U is the urinary concentration of the substance\r\n- V is the urinary flow rate \r\n- P is the plasma concentration of the substance\r\n\r\nGiven:\r\nU = 0 mg/ml\r\nV = 2 ml/min\r\nP = 13.6 mg/ml\r\n\r\nPlugging in the given values:\r\nC = (0 x 2) / 13.6\r\nC = 0\r\n\r\nThus, the renal clearance rate of substance \"X\" is 0 ml/min. This means that the substance is not being cleared from the plasma by the kidneys, suggesting that it is neither filtered nor secreted in the urine.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 374.","responses":[{"text":"13.6 ml/min","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2 ml/min","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1 ml/min","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"0 ml/min","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"0.5 ml/min","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13246,"text":"If a patient has a glomerular filtration rate of 100 ml/min and is known to be clearing a therapeutic drug at a rate of 150 ml/min, what is the most appropriate comment regarding the renal processing of this drug?","explanation":"The glomerular filtration rate (GFR) represents the rate at which the kidneys filter plasma. If a substance is neither reabsorbed nor secreted by the kidneys, its clearance would equal the GFR. When the clearance of a substance is greater than the GFR, it indicates that, in addition to being filtered, the substance is also actively secreted by the renal tubules. \r\n\r\nIn this case, the clearance of the drug (150 ml/min) is greater than the GFR (100 ml/min), indicating that the drug is not only filtered but also actively secreted by the kidneys. This additional clearance due to tubular secretion results in a total clearance rate that exceeds the GFR.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 343.","responses":[{"text":"Tm of drug has been exceeded, causing clearance to rise above GFR","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Overall processing of this drug is similar to amino acids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Since the clearance is greater than GFR, the drug must be secreted","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Since the clearance is greater than GFR, the drug must be reabsorbed","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"No evaluation can be made without further information","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13248,"text":"A one-year-old boy presents to the emergency with a complaint of weakness and growth retardation. He is lethargic and anemic. Blood analysis reveals megaloblastic anemia and urinalysis shows orotic aciduria. Which of the following compounds is most likely to alleviate his symptoms?","explanation":"The clinical presentation of the one-year-old boy suggests a defect in the de novo pyrimidine synthesis pathway, specifically orotic aciduria, which is caused by a deficiency in the enzyme uridine monophosphate (UMP) synthase. This enzyme normally converts orotic acid to UMP. Without it, orotic acid accumulates and is excreted in the urine.\r\n\r\nUridine can bypass the defective step in the pathway. Once provided, it can be converted to UMP, thereby replenishing the pyrimidine pool and alleviating the symptoms of the disorder. Megaloblastic anemia in the context of orotic aciduria is due to an inability to synthesize pyrimidine nucleotides, which are essential for DNA synthesis. By providing uridine, DNA synthesis in erythroid precursors is restored, and the anemia can be corrected.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 303.","responses":[{"text":"Adenine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Guanine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypoxanthine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thymidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Uridine","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13253,"text":"A one-year-old boy was admitted to the hospital with complaints of diarrhea and vomiting. On examination, he is lethargic, and weak and on pinching the abdominal skin it goes back very slowly. Which IV fluid should be given to rehydrate the child?","explanation":"The child described is showing signs of dehydration, specifically the delayed skin tuck (or tenting) indicates moderate to severe dehydration. In children with dehydration secondary to gastroenteritis (like diarrhea and vomiting), the primary concern is the loss of both water and essential electrolytes. \r\n\r\nRinger's lactate is an isotonic fluid that contains sodium, potassium, calcium, chloride, and lactate, which is metabolized to bicarbonate to help correct acidosis that often accompanies dehydration. It helps replenish both the fluid and the electrolytes lost, making it an ideal choice for rehydration in this clinical scenario.\r\n\r\nWhile normal saline could also be used for rehydration, Ringer's lactate is preferred due to its added benefits in electrolyte replacement and acid-base balance.","reference":"WHO, UNICEF. Integrated Management Of Neonatal \u0026 Childhood Illness. 1st ed. Ministry of National Health Services; 2017: Plan C for severe dehydration.","responses":[{"text":"Ringer's lactate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Normal saline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertonic saline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Haemacel","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"5% dextrose solution","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13256,"text":"A patient presents with confusion and has a sodium level of 123 mEq/l. He is diagnosed with syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion (SIADH). Which type of hyponatremia is this?","explanation":"Syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion (SIADH) is characterized by excessive release of antidiuretic hormone (ADH) leading to water retention and hyponatremia. In SIADH, there is an increase in total body water with a normal total body sodium level, resulting in dilutional hyponatremia.\r\n\r\nThis state corresponds to **euvolemic hyponatremia**, where there is neither visible edema nor clinical dehydration. The intravascular volume is normal, and the excess water is distributed throughout all body compartments.","reference":"Le T, Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2021. 31st ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 346.","responses":[{"text":"Antivolemic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pseudovolemic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypovolemic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypervolemic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Euvolemic","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13258,"text":"Which of the following organisms is the most common cause of community-acquired urinary tract infections?","explanation":"Community-acquired urinary tract infections (UTIs) are most frequently caused by **Escherichia Coli (E. coli)**, which is responsible for approximately 80% of these infections. \r\n\r\nE. coli is a normal inhabitant of the colon and can migrate from the rectal area to the urethral opening, leading to infection, especially in females due to the shorter length of the urethra and its proximity to the anus.\r\n\r\nOther organisms like Staphylococcus saprophyticus, Proteus mirabilis, Klebsiella, and Streptococcus faecalis also can cause UTIs but with much less frequency than E. coli. Notably, Staphylococcus saprophyticus is the second most common cause in young, sexually active women but still lags significantly behind E. coli.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 927.","responses":[{"text":"Klebsiella","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Proteus mirabilis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Escherichia Coli","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptococcus faecalis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Staphylococcus saprophyticus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13284,"text":"Which of the following is least frequently associated with focal segmental glomerulosclerosis?","explanation":"Focal segmental glomerulosclerosis (FSGS) is a kidney disease that affects the glomeruli. The term \"focal\" means that only some of the glomeruli are involved, and \"segmental\" means only part of an individual glomerulus is damaged.\r\n\r\n1. *Some glomeruli are sclerosed*: True. FSGS is characterized by scarring or \"sclerosis\" of some of the glomeruli.\r\n  \r\n2. *IgA deposition on immunofluorescence*: Least associated with FSGS. IgA deposition is more characteristically seen in IgA nephropathy, not in FSGS.\r\n  \r\n3. *IgM deposition on immunofluorescence*: While FSGS is primarily a non-immune complex-mediated disease, IgM can occasionally be seen, but it's not the main feature.\r\n  \r\n4. *Nephrotic syndrome*: Commonly associated. Patients with FSGS often present with nephrotic syndrome, which includes proteinuria, edema, hypoalbuminemia, and hyperlipidemia.\r\n  \r\n5. *Some glomeruli are normal*: True. FSGS affects only certain glomeruli and only parts of those glomeruli.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 915-916.","responses":[{"text":"IgM deposition on immunofluorescence","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Some glomeruli are sclerosed","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgA deposition on immunofluorescence","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Nephrotic syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Some glomeruli are normal","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13285,"text":"Anti-glomerular basement membrane antibody-induced glomerulonephritis accounts for less than 5% cases of human glomerulonephritis. Which of the following is the most appropriate example of this nephropathy?","explanation":"Anti-glomerular basement membrane (anti-GBM) antibody-induced glomerulonephritis is a type of rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis. One of the hallmark histological features of anti-GBM disease is the presence of crescents in most glomeruli.\r\n\r\n1. *Membranous nephropathy*: Characterized by thickening of the glomerular basement membrane without proliferation. It's primarily an immune complex-mediated disease.\r\n\r\n2. *Proliferation nephropathy*: A general term for glomerular diseases with increased cellularity. Not specific for anti-GBM disease.\r\n\r\n3. *Crescentic nephropathy*: This is synonymous with rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis (RPGN). Anti-GBM disease often presents as RPGN with crescent formation in glomeruli, making it the best choice.\r\n\r\n4. *Mesangioproliferative nephropathy*: Characterized by increased mesangial cellularity. It's seen in diseases like IgA nephropathy.\r\n\r\n5. *Membranoproliferative nephropathy*: Features glomerular basement membrane thickening with mesangial cell proliferation.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 909.","responses":[{"text":"Mesangioproliferative nephropathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Membranous nephropathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Membranoproliferative nephropathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Proliferation nephropathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crescentic nephropathy","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13286,"text":"Which of the following is least likely to be seen in nephrotic syndrome?","explanation":"Nephrotic syndrome is characterized by a set of clinical and laboratory findings:\r\n\r\n1. *Heavy proteinuria*: Typically exceeding 3.5 grams per day.\r\n2. *Hypoalbuminemia*: As a result of the significant loss of albumin in the urine.\r\n3. *Decreased plasma colloid osmotic pressure*: Due to the loss of albumin, leading to edema.\r\n4. *Selective proteinuria*: Initially, there's a loss of primarily albumin, making it \"selective\". Over time, it can become non-selective with the loss of other plasma proteins.\r\n\r\n*Hematuria*, on the other hand, is the presence of red blood cells in the urine. While it can be seen in nephritic syndrome (which is a different renal pathology), it is not a typical feature of nephrotic syndrome and is therefore the least likely to be observed among the options provided.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 911.","responses":[{"text":"Hematuria","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Heavy proteinuria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Selective proteinuria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased plasma colloid osmotic pressure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypoalbuminemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13287,"text":"Which of the following is least likely to be correct about xanthogranulomatous pyelonephritis?","explanation":"Xanthogranulomatous pyelonephritis (XGP) is an uncommon, severe form of chronic pyelonephritis:\r\n\r\n1. *Rare form of chronic pyelonephritis*: XGP is indeed a rare form of chronic pyelonephritis, typically associated with long-standing urinary tract obstruction and infection.\r\n\r\n2. *Accumulation of foamy macrophages with plasma cells, lymphocytes, and giant cells*: Histologically, XGP is characterized by the presence of these cellular components.\r\n\r\n3. *Shows large yellow nodules*: Grossly, the kidney contains large, yellow nodules, lending to its name, \"xantho-\" meaning yellow.\r\n\r\n4. *Grossly resembles renal cell carcinoma*: Clinically and grossly, XGP can mimic a renal neoplasm, like renal cell carcinoma, which sometimes makes it challenging to diagnose without histological confirmation.\r\n\r\nHowever, XGP is not typically associated with polyomavirus infection. This infection is more commonly associated with other renal pathologies like BK virus nephropathy, especially in immunocompromised patients.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 931.","responses":[{"text":"Grossly resembles renal cell carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rare form of chronic pyelonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Associated with polyomavirus infection","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Accumulation of foamy macrophages with plasma cells, lymphocytes and giant cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shows large yellow nodules","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13288,"text":"Which of the following statements is most appropriate regarding renal transplantation?","explanation":"In renal transplantation, ensuring compatibility between the donor and the recipient is crucial for graft survival and minimizing the chances of graft rejection. There are two primary aspects to consider: HLA matching and blood type compatibility.\r\n\r\n**ABO compatibility**: This refers to ensuring that the donor and recipient have compatible blood types. Blood group compatibility is fundamental for kidney transplantation. ABO-incompatible transplants can lead to immediate graft rejection due to pre-existing antibodies against the blood group antigens of the donor organ. Hence, ensuring ABO compatibility is essential to prevent hyperacute rejection.\r\n\r\n**HLA compatibility**: Although ideal, perfect HLA matches are not always feasible, and kidney transplants can be done with various levels of HLA mismatches, albeit with potentially different outcomes and increased need for immunosuppression.\r\n\r\nTherefore, while HLA matching is preferred and beneficial for graft survival, ABO compatibility is essential to prevent immediate organ rejection.","reference":"MEHRA N, CHOPRA G. Importance of donor selection in renal transplantation. Medical Journal, Armed Forces India. Published July 1994. Accessed December 10, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5529729/","responses":[{"text":"ABO compatibility between donor and recipient is essential","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Immunosuppressant drugs are prescribed to selected transplant patients","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HLA compatibility for minor antigens is not required","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Allergen test is performed on potential recipient","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HLA compatibility is sometimes not required","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13289,"text":"A researcher is conducting a research study to find the prevalence of diabetes mellitus in Karachi city. Which of the following epidemiological study design is the most appropriate for this research?","explanation":"When determining the prevalence of a specific disease or condition in a population at a particular point in time, a **cross-sectional study** is the most appropriate epidemiological study design. \r\n\r\nIn a cross-sectional study, researchers observe and analyze data from a defined population at a single specific point in time (or over a short period). The study does not involve interventions or follow-ups, which makes it efficient for assessing prevalence. For the given research objective of finding the prevalence of diabetes mellitus in Karachi city, the cross-sectional design will allow the researcher to assess the number of existing cases of diabetes in the city's population over a defined short period, providing an accurate snapshot of the current situation.\r\n\r\nOther study designs like cohort, case-control, and experimental are more suitable for studying causality, risk factors, or outcomes of interventions rather than prevalence.","reference":"Kestenbaum B. Epidemiology and Biostatistics; An Introduction to Clinical Research. 2nd ed. Springer Nature; 2019: 39","responses":[{"text":"Cohort study","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Case-control study","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cross-sectional study","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Case series","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Experimental study","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13292,"text":"During your posting in the behavioral sciences department, you were taught about informational care and how sharing the patient's personal information is sometimes important for the patient's care. Which of the following individuals is \"authorized\" to know the patient's personal information?","explanation":"Protecting the confidentiality of patient information is a fundamental principle in healthcare. However, for the provision of comprehensive care, sometimes sharing of patient's personal information within the healthcare team becomes necessary. \r\n\r\nThe most appropriate individual to have access to a patient's personal information is **another worker from the care team providing support to the individual**. This is because they are directly involved in the care and treatment of the patient and require this information to provide adequate and accurate care.\r\n\r\nWhile family members may sometimes have access depending on patient consent or the nature of the illness, they aren't inherently \"authorized.\" Other health workers, senior workers not involved in direct care, and colleagues typically do not have inherent rights to access personal patient information unless specific conditions or consents apply.","reference":"Dow lecture slides, Renal-I Module, Behavioural Science slides, Topic: Information Care.","responses":[{"text":"A colleague of the patient","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Another worker from the care team providing support to the individual","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"A senior worker not involved in supporting the individual","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A family member of the patient","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Another health worker from another team providing care to another individual","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13296,"text":"A patient presents to the emergency room with complaints of diarrhea and vomiting for one day. He is semi-conscious and severely dehydrated. What is the first-line management in this patient?","explanation":"In a severely dehydrated patient who is semi-conscious, the primary concern is restoring fluid balance and preventing complications like shock or organ damage. \r\n\r\nThe most effective and immediate way to manage severe dehydration, especially in a patient with altered consciousness, is **IV fluid replacement**. This approach allows for rapid rehydration and correction of electrolyte imbalances. Intravenous access facilitates the quick delivery of fluids, bypassing the gastrointestinal tract, which can be compromised in the context of diarrhea and vomiting.\r\n\r\nOral fluid replacement is typically reserved for milder cases where the patient is alert and can drink. Antibiotics, whether oral or IV, would be considered based on the suspected underlying cause (e.g., bacterial infection), but fluid replacement remains the immediate priority.","reference":"Taylor K, Jones EB. Adult dehydration. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed December 10, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK555956/","responses":[{"text":"IV antibiotics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IV fluid replacement","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Oral antibiotics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"KYB diet","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oral fluid replacement","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13300,"text":"In a patient with severe dehydration, which organ/s become/s non-functional almost immediately?","explanation":"In the context of severe dehydration, the **kidneys** are among the first organs to be affected. The primary role of the kidneys is to filter blood and regulate fluid and electrolyte balance. When the body is severely dehydrated, blood volume decreases, leading to reduced renal perfusion. This triggers the kidneys to conserve water, resulting in decreased urine output (oliguria) or complete cessation of urine (anuria). Prolonged or severe reduction in kidney perfusion can lead to acute kidney injury. \r\n\r\nWhile other organs like the liver and pancreas are affected by dehydration, they do not become non-functional as immediately as the kidneys. The lungs and eyes are not directly compromised by dehydration in the same manner, though dehydration can lead to dry mucous membranes, including those of the eyes.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 585.","responses":[{"text":"Eyes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Kidneys","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lungs","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13301,"text":"Which of the following is a cause of pre-renal acute kidney failure?","explanation":"Pre-renal acute kidney injury (AKI) is primarily caused by decreased perfusion of the kidneys. The main factors contributing to this can be reduced blood volume or decreased effective blood volume, without direct damage to the kidneys.\r\n\r\n**Profuse diarrhea** can lead to significant fluid loss, resulting in reduced blood volume and thereby reduced renal perfusion. When the kidneys sense this decrease in blood flow, they attempt to conserve water and sodium, which can be observed as oliguria (reduced urine output).\r\n\r\nWhile prostate hypertrophy and prostate cancer can lead to post-renal AKI due to obstruction of the urinary tract, nephrotic syndrome and acute glomerulonephritis are intrinsic renal causes of AKI, where the damage occurs directly within the kidney.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 585.","responses":[{"text":"Prostrate hypertrophy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Profuse diarrhea","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Nephrotic syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prostate cancer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute glomerulonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13302,"text":"A 65-year-old female with chronic kidney disease secondary to hypertension has low erythropoietin levels. Which of the following conditions is the patient at risk of developing?","explanation":"Erythropoietin (EPO) is a hormone primarily produced by the kidneys. Its main function is to stimulate the bone marrow to produce red blood cells. In chronic kidney disease (CKD), especially when secondary to conditions like hypertension, the damaged kidneys often fail to produce adequate amounts of EPO. As a result, there's a decreased stimulus for red blood cell production in the bone marrow, leading to a condition called renal anemia.\r\n\r\nAnemia is characterized by a reduced number of circulating red blood cells, leading to symptoms like fatigue, pallor, and shortness of breath. It's one of the common complications of CKD. In cases with low EPO levels due to CKD, treatment often involves the administration of synthetic erythropoietin to stimulate red blood cell production.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 592.","responses":[{"text":"Anemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypomagnesemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypophosphatemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypokalemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypercalcemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13303,"text":"What is the investigation of choice to diagnose vesicoureteric reflux in a male toddler?","explanation":"Vesicoureteric reflux (VUR) refers to the backward flow of urine from the bladder into the ureters. In children, particularly toddlers, diagnosing this condition is essential as it can lead to recurrent urinary tract infections and kidney damage.\r\n\r\nMicturating cystourethrography (MCUG) is the investigation of choice for diagnosing VUR. During this procedure, a catheter is placed into the bladder, and the bladder is filled with a contrast medium. X-ray images are taken while the patient is micturating (voiding). If there's reflux, the contrast will be seen moving from the bladder back into the ureters and sometimes even up to the kidneys.\r\n\r\nWhile other imaging modalities can provide information about the urinary tract, MCUG is specifically designed to visualize the reflux during the act of micturition, making it the best tool for this particular diagnosis.","reference":"Banker H, Aeddula NR. Vesicoureteral reflux. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed December 10, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK563262/","responses":[{"text":"IV urography","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CT urography","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"MR urethrography","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ultrasound bladder with pre and post void volumes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Micturating cystourethrography","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13305,"text":"Which of the following vessels gives rise to the renal arteries?","explanation":"The kidneys are retroperitoneal organs that play a vital role in filtration and excretion. They receive a significant blood supply, which is derived from the renal arteries. The renal arteries originate directly from the abdominal aorta, typically just below the level of the superior mesenteric artery. Each kidney typically has one main renal artery, but there can be variations with multiple renal arteries present in some individuals.\r\n\r\nThe abdominal aorta is the main arterial trunk of the abdomen that supplies oxygenated blood to the abdominal and pelvic organs as well as the lower limbs.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 520 fig. 5.83.","responses":[{"text":"Lobar artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gonadal vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Abdominal aorta","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Common iliac artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior vena cava","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13307,"text":"Which of the following structures enters the kidney at the hilum and brings blood to the kidneys?","explanation":"The kidneys are paired retroperitoneal organs responsible for filtering blood and eliminating waste. For efficient filtration, they require a significant blood supply. This supply is provided by the renal arteries. The renal artery arises directly from the abdominal aorta and enters each kidney at the hilum. The hilum is a concave notch located medially on each kidney, where the renal artery enters, the renal vein exits, and the ureter also begins its descent.\r\n\r\nOnce inside the kidney, the renal artery divides into smaller branches to supply the various parts of the kidney. Blood is then filtered within the kidney and returned to the heart via the renal vein, which eventually drains into the inferior vena cava. The renal artery, thus, plays a crucial role in bringing oxygenated blood to the kidneys for filtration.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 521, fig 5.84.","responses":[{"text":"Abdominal aorta","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Common iliac artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior vena cava","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13309,"text":"Which of the following are direct branches of the renal arteries?","explanation":"The renal arteries are responsible for delivering blood to the kidneys for filtration. Once the renal artery reaches the hilum of the kidney, it branches out into multiple segmental arteries. These segmental arteries are the direct branches of the renal arteries and provide the main vascular supply to distinct regions or segments of the kidney.\r\n\r\nFollowing the segmental arteries, there's further division leading to:\r\n- **Interlobar arteries**: which travel between the renal pyramids.\r\n- **Arcuate arteries**: which run along the base of the pyramids at the corticomedullary junction.\r\n- **Interlobular arteries**: that move radially into the renal cortex.\r\n\r\nThe afferent arterioles branch off from the interlobular arteries and lead to the glomeruli for filtration.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 520.","responses":[{"text":"Afferent arteries","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lobar arteries","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Segmental arteries","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lobular arteries","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arcuate arteries","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13313,"text":"Which part of the renal tubule is impermeable to water, while solutes can pass out passively into medullary interstitial space?","explanation":"The nephron, the functional unit of the kidney, features segments with specific tasks for fluid and solute handling. The thin ascending limb of the loop of Henle is unique because it's impermeable to water. This means water can't be reabsorbed back into the bloodstream from this segment. However, solutes, primarily sodium and chloride ions, can passively diffuse out of the thin ascending limb into the surrounding medullary interstitial space. This passive movement contributes to the hyperosmolarity of the renal medulla, which is essential for the kidney's ability to concentrate urine. Consequently, as the filtrate moves through the thin ascending limb, it becomes increasingly dilute, setting the stage for further processing in the nephron's subsequent segments.","reference":"Costanzo LS. Physiology. 6th ed. Elsevier; 2018: 283.","responses":[{"text":"Thin ascending limb of loop of Henle","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Proximal convoluted tubule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Distal convoluted tubule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thick ascending limb of loop of Henle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Descending limb of loop of Henle","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13314,"text":"In which segment of the renal tubule are the sodium-hydrogen antiporters that are involved in hydrogen ion secretion located?","explanation":"The proximal convoluted tubule (PCT) plays a pivotal role in the renal handling of various solutes and the maintenance of acid-base balance. The sodium-hydrogen antiporters, or exchangers (NHE), are predominantly located on the apical membrane of the cells lining the PCT. These antiporters facilitate the secretion of hydrogen ions (H⁺) into the tubular lumen in exchange for the reabsorption of sodium ions (Na⁺) into the cell. This process aids in bicarbonate (HCO₃⁻) reabsorption by the tubular cells, as the secreted H⁺ ions combine with filtered bicarbonate to form carbonic acid, which then dissociates to water and carbon dioxide. The reclamation of bicarbonate is essential for maintaining the acid-base balance in the body.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 359.","responses":[{"text":"Loop of Henle - thin segment","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Collecting duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Proximal convoluted tubule","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Distal convoluted tubule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Loop of Henle - thick segment","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13315,"text":"A 46-year-old male presents to the emergency room with severe right toe pain. On examination, he had a temperature of 100.8° F, and he was moderately distressed about the pain in his toe. The right big toe was swollen, warm, red, and exquisitely tender. Synovial joint fluid was obtained and revealed rod or needle-shaped crystals. Which enzyme(s) is/are deficient in this patient?","explanation":"The patient's presentation is suggestive of acute gouty arthritis, characterized by the deposition of monosodium urate crystals in the joint. Gout is often associated with hyperuricemia, an elevated level of uric acid in the blood. Uric acid is the end product of purine metabolism in humans.\r\n\r\nHypoxanthine-guanine phosphoribosyl transferase (HGPRT) is an enzyme involved in the salvage pathway of purine metabolism. A deficiency or absence of HGPRT leads to decreased recycling of purines, causing an overproduction of uric acid. This overproduction can lead to conditions like gout due to the accumulation and crystallization of uric acid in joints. The rod or needle-shaped crystals observed in the joint fluid are monosodium urate crystals, consistent with gouty arthritis.","reference":"(1) Murray RK, Victor WR, Bender D, Kathleen MB, Weil PA, Kennelly PJ. Harper’s Illustrated Biochemistry. 28th ed. McGraw-Hill Professional; 2009: 300.\r\n(2) Turco S. USMLE® Step 1 Lecture Notes 2021: Biochemistry and Medical Genetics. Kaplan Publishing; 2021: 294.","responses":[{"text":"Hypoxanthine-guanine phosphoribosyl transferase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Alkaline phosphatase, Phosphoribosyl pyrophosphate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phosphoribosyl pyrophosphate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypoxanthine-guanine phosphoribosyl transferase, Phosphoribosyl pyrophosphate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adenosine deaminase, Hypoxanthine-guanine phosphoribosyl transferase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13316,"text":"Which of the following best describes the urine of diabetic patients?","explanation":"In diabetes mellitus, especially when it is poorly controlled, there is an elevated blood glucose level. When the renal threshold for glucose (usually around 180 mg/dL) is exceeded, glucose starts to spill into the urine. The osmotic nature of glucose causes water to be drawn into the urine, leading to polyuria (increased volume of urine). Consequently, because of the presence of excess glucose, the specific gravity of the urine also increases. The specific gravity is a measure of the urine's density compared to water, and it reflects the solute concentration in the urine. In the context of diabetes, the specific gravity rises due to glucose's osmotic effect.\r\n\r\nThus, in diabetic patients, especially when their blood sugar is not well-managed, the urine is characterized by both increased volume and increased specific gravity.","reference":"Akarsu E, Buyukhatipoglu H, Aktaran S, Geyik R. The value of urine specific gravity in detecting diabetes insipidus in a patient with uncontrolled diabetes mellitus. Journal of General Internal Medicine. Published November 2006. Accessed December 10, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1831666/","responses":[{"text":"Decreased volume, increased specific gravity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased volume, increased specific gravity","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased volume, decreased specific gravity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Normal volume, increased specific gravity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Normal volume, decreased specific gravity","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13317,"text":"Which of the following serves as a cofactor in de novo purine synthesis?","explanation":"De novo purine synthesis is the biochemical pathway by which purine nucleotides are synthesized anew, rather than being recycled. One of the critical steps in this pathway involves the formation of 10-formyltetrahydrofolate from folate. This molecule then acts as a one-carbon donor in several reactions during purine synthesis. Specifically, 10-formyltetrahydrofolate donates one-carbon units for the formation of the purine ring.\r\n\r\nFolate, or vitamin B9, is essential for this and many other one-carbon transfer reactions in the body. In addition to its role in purine synthesis, folate also plays a crucial role in thymidine synthesis, which is necessary for DNA replication. A deficiency in folate can lead to various health issues, including megaloblastic anemia and elevated levels of homocysteine.","reference":"Pareek V, Pedley AM, Benkovic SJ. Human de novo purine biosynthesis. Critical reviews in biochemistry and molecular biology. Published February 2021. Accessed December 10, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7869020/","responses":[{"text":"Folate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Thiamine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Biotin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Flavin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Caltrate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13318,"text":"A 60-year-old male with a history of diabetes and chronic kidney failure presents to the clinic with complaints of dyspnea, cough, malaise, and fever for 15 days. How can the glomerular filtration rate be determined in this patient?","explanation":"Glomerular filtration rate (GFR) is a key indicator of renal function, and it measures how effectively the kidneys filter blood. Creatinine clearance is the most commonly used clinical test to estimate GFR. Creatinine, a waste product of muscle metabolism, is produced at a constant rate and is freely filtered by the glomeruli but not reabsorbed. By measuring the concentration of creatinine in the blood and in a 24-hour urine collection, the GFR can be approximated. The formula for creatinine clearance is:\r\n\r\nCreatinine clearance = Volume of urine (mL) x Urine creatinine (mg/dL) / Plasma creatinine (mg/dL) x Time (min)","reference":"(1) Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 361.\r\n(2) Berg A. Which Methods for Determining Glomerular Filtration Rate Most Strongly Associate with Risk of Progression of Kidney Disease? https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7295158/","responses":[{"text":"Urinalysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum pyruvate dehydrogenase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IV pyelogram","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal scan","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Creatinine clearance","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13319,"text":"A 55-year-old male with COPD presents to the clinic with increased severity of shortness of breath. His immediate arterial blood gases show respiratory acidosis. What is the first step in the interpretation of arterial blood gases?","explanation":"When interpreting arterial blood gases (ABGs), the initial step is to assess the pH of the blood. The pH will provide an immediate clue as to whether the primary disturbance is acidemia or alkalemia. If the pH is lower than the reference range (usually \u003c7.35), it indicates acidemia, while if it's higher (usually \u003e7.45), it indicates alkalemia. After determining the pH, the next steps involve evaluating PaCO₂ and HCO₃ levels to discern whether the primary disturbance is respiratory or metabolic in nature. For a patient with COPD presenting with worsening symptoms, respiratory acidosis (elevated PaCO₂) is a common finding. However, the starting point for ABG interpretation always remains the pH.","reference":"ood P, Paul G, Puri S. Interpretation of arterial blood gas. Indian Journal of Critical Care Medicine : Peer-reviewed, Official Publication of Indian Society of Critical Care Medicine. Published 2010. Accessed December 10, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2936733/","responses":[{"text":"PaCO₂","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anion gap","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HCO₃ level","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"pH of blood","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Delta-delta gap","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13320,"text":"A 40-year-old female with a history of breast carcinoma was brought to the critical care unit with the complication of metastasis. They were counseled about minimal chances of survival. The family was not convinced by your opinion and wished to consult a second specialist. What is the responsibility of the doctor in this scenario?","explanation":"In clinical practice, it is a patient's right to seek a second opinion if they are uncertain about a diagnosis or recommended treatment. The physician's responsibility is to support and respect the patient's and their family's decision to seek a second opinion, ensuring that they have all the relevant information and records. This helps maintain trust and open communication. Denying or criticizing the wish for a second opinion can erode trust. It's also important for the physician to be open to the possibility that another specialist may have a different perspective or approach. Additionally, offering palliative care and counseling is essential for managing symptoms and providing psychological support, but the primary responsibility in the scenario described is to support the decision for a second opinion.","reference":"How to seek a second opinion :: east lancashire hospitals nhs trust. Accessed December 10, 2022. https://elht.nhs.uk/patients/how-seek-second-opinion#:~:text=The%20General%20Medical%20Council%2C%20which,opinion%2C%20they%20should%20do%20so","responses":[{"text":"Offer psychoeducation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Offer palliative care","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Support the decision of second opinion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Discharge the patient immediately","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Facilitate by counseling","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16008,"text":"What percentage of the total body weight does the extra-cellular fluid (ECF) account for?","explanation":"The body's total water content is roughly 60% of the body weight in an average adult male. This water is divided into intracellular fluid (ICF) and extracellular fluid (ECF) compartments. The ICF accounts for about 2/3 of the total body water, or approximately 40% of the total body weight. The ECF, on the other hand, accounts for the remaining 1/3 of the total body water, which equates to about 20% of the body weight. The ECF can be further subdivided into the interstitial fluid (about 15% of body weight) and the plasma volume (about 5% of body weight).","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 307.","responses":[{"text":"15%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"10%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"70%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"5%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"20%","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16009,"text":"The renal sinus is a space within the kidney containing all the structures responsible for draining urine into the ureter. Which of the following structures is present in this space?","explanation":"The renal sinus is a cavity within the kidney that houses the renal pelvis, calyces, blood vessels, nerves, and fat. The renal pyramids, medullary rays, cortical columns, and renal medulla are all integral parts of the renal parenchyma (functional tissue) and do not lie within the renal sinus. The major calyces are extensions of the renal pelvis, which collect urine from the minor calyces and subsequently direct it into the renal pelvis and ureter. Thus, the major calyces are structures within the renal sinus responsible for assisting in the drainage of urine.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 378.","responses":[{"text":"Major calyx","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal pyramids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal medulla","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cortical columns","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medullary rays","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16010,"text":"Which of the following is the most common site for an ectopic kidney?","explanation":"An ectopic kidney refers to a kidney that is located in an abnormal position. The most common site for an ectopic kidney is the pelvis. During the embryonic development, kidneys originate in the pelvis and then ascend to their normal lumbar position. Sometimes, one or both kidneys fail to ascend properly, resulting in a pelvic kidney. This is often termed \"pelvic kidney.\" The kidney can function normally, but it may have a different orientation, blood supply, and drainage than a typically located kidney. It's important to recognize a pelvic kidney, especially before procedures like surgery or certain radiographic studies, to avoid inadvertent injury. Other ectopic sites such as the upper abdomen, lower abdomen, inguinal canal, and perineum are less common compared to the pelvic location.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 525.","responses":[{"text":"Upper abdomen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Perineum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inguinal canal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lower abdomen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pelvis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16011,"text":"Which of the following results in an uninhibited neurogenic bladder?","explanation":"An uninhibited neurogenic bladder is associated with partial injury of the spinal cord or brainstem. This occurs when there is disruption of the descending inhibitory pathways, but the reflex arcs at the sacral level are intact. Due to this partial injury, the micturition center in the sacral spinal cord loses its inhibitory control from higher centers, but it still can mediate the reflexive emptying of the bladder. This leads to frequent, involuntary contractions of the bladder, causing urinary urgency, frequency, and sometimes incontinence. Such a situation differs from complete spinal cord injuries above the sacral region, where an initial phase of an \"atonic bladder\" (where the bladder loses its tone and doesn't contract) may follow, succeeded by the development of an automatic bladder due to the re-establishment of the reflex arc.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 328.","responses":[{"text":"Pelvic nerve injury","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urinary tract infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Partial injury of spinal cord or brainstem","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tabes dorsalis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spinal cord injury above sacral region","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16012,"text":"Which of the following hormones or autocoids can increase the glomerular filtration rate (GFR) by decreasing vascular resistance in the glomerular capillaries?","explanation":"The glomerular filtration rate (GFR) is influenced by the balance between vasoconstrictor and vasodilator factors acting on the afferent and efferent arterioles of the renal glomerulus. Endothelial derived nitric oxide (NO) is a potent vasodilator. It decreases the vascular resistance of the glomerular capillaries by relaxing the vascular smooth muscle cells. This relaxation results in vasodilation of the afferent arterioles, leading to an increased renal blood flow and consequently a higher GFR. On the contrary, agents like norepinephrine, epinephrine, and angiotensin II predominantly cause vasoconstriction, which can decrease GFR. Angiotensin I is a precursor to angiotensin II and by itself does not have significant vasoactive properties.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 338.","responses":[{"text":"Endothelial derived nitric oxide","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Angiotensin II","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Norepinephrine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epinephrine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Angiotensin I","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16013,"text":"A 5-year-old boy presents to the outpatient clinic with generalized edema and periorbital edema. Blood tests and urine analysis reveal hypoalbuminemia, lipiduria, and 3.7 g proteinuria. A renal biopsy is performed. Which of the following electron microscopic features is most likely to be present in this case?","explanation":"The clinical presentation of the boy suggests nephrotic syndrome. Nephrotic syndrome is characterized by heavy proteinuria, hypoalbuminemia, edema, and lipiduria. The most common cause of primary nephrotic syndrome in children is Minimal Change Disease (MCD). Electron microscopy in MCD reveals the effacement (flattening) of the foot processes of the podocytes, but immune deposits are typically absent. This feature distinguishes MCD from other forms of nephrotic syndrome. The exact pathogenesis remains unclear, but it is thought that a circulating factor may lead to podocyte injury. While the microscopic appearance of glomeruli on light microscopy is usually normal, electron microscopy provides the defining feature for diagnosis.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 127, 128.","responses":[{"text":"Subendothelial deposits","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crescent shaped glomeruli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Effacement of foot process but no deposits","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Thick glomerular basement membrane with immune complex deposition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Subepithelial deposits","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16014,"text":"The parents of an 11-year-old mentally impaired male child visit a local clinic. The father tells the doctor that he has 7 other children to support and someone suggested that he could sell the kidney of his mentally impaired son. What is the correct legal implication in this case according to the \"Transplantation of Human Organs and Tissues Act 2010\"?","explanation":"The \"Transplantation of Human Organs and Tissues Act 2010\" clearly states that it is illegal to buy or sell human organs and tissues. Commercial trading of organs is strictly prohibited. The purpose of this legislation is to prevent exploitation of the poor and vulnerable and to stop the black market for organs. In the given scenario, regardless of the child's mental impairment or the financial situation of the family, selling the kidney is illegal. The law also emphasizes the importance of voluntary and informed consent, primarily from living donors. The consent must be free from any undue influence, coercion, or monetary incentive. Thus, the selling of the kidney of the mentally impaired child, even with parental consent, is a violation of the law.","reference":"Transplantation of human organs and tissues act 2010. Published March 18, 2010. Accessed May 30, 2023. http://punjablaws.gov.pk/laws/2428a.html","responses":[{"text":"It is illegal to sell a kidney and should not be done","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It is legal because patient is mentally impaired","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It can only be donated to a relative","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It can be sold since parents provide their consent","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Consent of patient is needed","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16015,"text":"The enzyme carbonic anhydrase catalyzes the formation of which of the following compounds?","explanation":"Carbonic anhydrase is an enzyme that catalyzes the reversible hydration of carbon dioxide to form carbonic acid (H₂CO₃). The reaction is as follows:\r\n\r\nCO₂ + H₂O ↔ H₂CO₃\r\n\r\nCarbonic anhydrase is especially active in red blood cells and certain renal tubule cells. In red blood cells, it facilitates the transport of CO₂ from tissues to the lungs for excretion. In the kidneys, it plays a critical role in the acid-base homeostasis by helping in the reabsorption of bicarbonate ions. It does not catalyze the formation of other acids like H₂PO₄, HNO₃, H₃PO₄, or H₂SO₄. H₂CO₃ can dissociate further to release a proton (H⁺) and a bicarbonate ion (HCO₃⁻), making it central to many physiological processes.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 30.","responses":[{"text":"H₃PO₄","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"H₂CO₃","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"H₂PO₄","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"H₂SO₄","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HNO₃","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16016,"text":"The Na-K-2Cl cotransporters are present in which of the following parts of a nephron?","explanation":"The Na-K-2Cl cotransporter, also known as the NKCC2 transporter, is predominantly located in the thick ascending limb of the loop of Henle in the nephron. This transporter simultaneously moves sodium (Na⁺), potassium (K⁺), and two chloride (Cl⁻) ions from the tubular lumen into the epithelial cells. Its function is crucial for the reabsorption of these ions. The thick ascending limb of the loop of Henle is responsible for the reabsorption of a significant fraction of the filtered load of sodium and chloride. This segment of the nephron is impermeable to water, so the reabsorption of solutes without water creates a diluting segment, which is essential for the kidney's ability to produce dilute urine. The action of the Na-K-2Cl cotransporter is inhibited by loop diuretics like furosemide, leading to increased diuresis.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 351.","responses":[{"text":"Proximal convoluted tubule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thick ascending limb of loop of Henle","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Descending limb of loop of Henle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Distal convoluted tubule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thin descending limb of loop of Henle","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16017,"text":"The synthesis of deoxyribonucleotides from ribonucleotides requires the enzyme ribonucleotide reductase. Which of the following is a cofactor for this enzyme?","explanation":"Ribonucleotide reductase is the key enzyme responsible for the conversion of ribonucleotides to deoxyribonucleotides, a crucial step in DNA synthesis. This enzyme requires a reducing agent to carry out its function. Thioredoxin is a small protein with a redox-active disulfide/dithiol group within its conserved CXXC motif. In the context of ribonucleotide reductase action, thioredoxin provides the reducing equivalents necessary for the conversion of ribonucleotides to deoxyribonucleotides. Thus, thioredoxin acts as a cofactor for ribonucleotide reductase. It's worth noting that thioredoxin, once oxidized during the reaction, is regenerated by the action of another enzyme, thioredoxin reductase, in the presence of NADPH.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 297.","responses":[{"text":"Riboflavin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thioredoxin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyridoxine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin B12","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Folate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16018,"text":"Which of the following is the most common route of spread of acute pyelonephritis?","explanation":"Acute pyelonephritis is most commonly caused by an ascending infection, beginning in the urethra and ascending through the bladder into the ureters and then into the renal pelvis and renal parenchyma. The majority of urinary tract infections (UTIs) start in the lower urinary tract. When such an infection is limited to the bladder, it's termed cystitis. If the bacteria ascend further into the kidneys, acute pyelonephritis can develop. Escherichia coli is the most frequent causative organism. Factors that predispose to ascending infections include vesicoureteral reflux, urinary tract obstructions, catheterization, and pregnancy. While hematogenous spread is another route of kidney infection, it's less common compared to the ascending route for acute pyelonephritis.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 132.","responses":[{"text":"Direct spread from nearby viscera","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"From peritoneal cavity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ascending spread from urethra and bladder","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hematogenous spread","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphogenous spread","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16019,"text":"In the process of pyrimidine metabolism, the deamination of cytosine produces which of the following compounds?","explanation":"In pyrimidine metabolism, the deamination of cytosine leads to the formation of uracil. This reaction involves the removal of an amino group (-NH2) from cytosine and its replacement with a keto group (=O). Deamination reactions in nucleotide metabolism are catalyzed by specific deaminases. In this case, cytosine deaminase catalyzes the conversion of cytosine to uracil. It's essential to note that while cytosine is found in DNA, uracil is typically found in RNA. During the synthesis of RNA (transcription), adenine in DNA base pairs with uracil in RNA.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 428.","responses":[{"text":"Uracil","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Thiouracil","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cytidylic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thiamine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adenylic acid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16020,"text":"A doctor is performing a nephrostomy. Which of the following regions of the body is most appropriate to approach the kidney?","explanation":"A nephrostomy, which involves creating an opening between the kidney and the skin, is typically approached through the posterior abdominal wall. The kidneys lie retroperitoneally (behind the peritoneum) against the posterior abdominal wall. The upper poles of the kidneys are closer to the 11th and 12th ribs, making this area an optimal site for surgical intervention. By accessing the kidneys through the posterior abdominal wall, the surgeon can avoid many of the abdominal contents found in the anterior and pelvic regions. Furthermore, this approach minimizes potential damage to other structures and offers a direct route to the kidneys.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 383.","responses":[{"text":"Anterior abdominal wall","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pelvic cavity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior abdominal wall","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior part of pelvic cavity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior part of the pelvic cavity","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16021,"text":"Mycophenolic acid is used as an immunosuppressant drug to prevent graft rejection after transplant. Which of the following enzymes is inhibited by this drug?","explanation":"Mycophenolic acid (MPA) is an immunosuppressant drug primarily used to prevent graft rejection post-transplant. The principal mechanism of action of MPA is the inhibition of the enzyme inosine monophosphate (IMP) dehydrogenase. This enzyme plays a pivotal role in the de novo synthesis of guanosine nucleotides. By inhibiting IMP dehydrogenase, MPA deprives proliferating T and B lymphocytes of the essential guanosine nucleotides, thereby suppressing their proliferation. This reduction in lymphocyte proliferation helps in preventing the immune-mediated graft rejection. It's worth noting that the salvage pathway remains unaffected by MPA, but lymphocytes are more dependent on the de novo pathway for their guanosine nucleotide needs, making them particularly susceptible to the effects of MPA.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 295.","responses":[{"text":"Phosphoribosyl pyrophosphate (PRPP) synthetase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adenosine deaminase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adenylosuccinate synthetase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inosine monophosphate (IMP) dehydrogenase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Dihydrofolate reductase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16022,"text":"Which of the following factors help distinguish that hematuria is of renal origin and not from the bladder?","explanation":"Hematuria, or the presence of blood in the urine, can arise from various regions within the urinary tract, including the kidneys, ureters, bladder, and urethra. Determining the origin is crucial for appropriate diagnosis and management. Among the options listed, RBC casts are indicative of a renal origin for the hematuria. \r\n\r\nRBC casts form within the tubular lumen of the kidneys when red blood cells aggregate and become enmeshed within a proteinaceous matrix. The presence of RBC casts in the urine signifies glomerular or tubulointerstitial inflammation and is a hallmark of glomerular bleeding. In contrast, conditions affecting the lower urinary tract (e.g., bladder infections or tumors) will produce hematuria but not RBC casts.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V, Qiu C, et al., eds. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2023. 33rd ed. McGraw Hill; 2023: 614.","responses":[{"text":"RBC casts","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemoglobinuria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sterile pyuria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"WBC casts","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gross hematuria","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16023,"text":"Under the action of which of the following hormones is potassium secreted from the principal cells of the late distal tubules and collecting ducts?","explanation":"Aldosterone, a mineralocorticoid hormone produced by the zona glomerulosa of the adrenal cortex, plays a pivotal role in regulating sodium and potassium balance in the body. When aldosterone levels increase, it acts on the principal cells of the late distal tubules and collecting ducts in the kidneys. Here, it stimulates the insertion of sodium channels on the luminal surface, promoting sodium reabsorption. Concurrently, aldosterone increases the activity of sodium-potassium ATPase pumps on the basolateral membrane, which facilitates the reabsorption of sodium into the blood while pumping potassium into the cell. As a result, there is an increased intracellular potassium concentration, which then drives potassium secretion into the tubular lumen via potassium channels. Therefore, aldosterone leads to increased sodium reabsorption and enhanced potassium secretion.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 387.","responses":[{"text":"Angiotensin I","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cortisol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aldosterone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Angiotensin II","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antidiuretic hormone","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16024,"text":"Which of the following ions is secreted by the principal cells when stimulated by aldosterone?","explanation":"Aldosterone is a steroid hormone produced by the adrenal cortex that primarily targets the principal cells of the distal tubules and collecting ducts in the kidneys. Its main role is in the regulation of sodium and potassium balance. When aldosterone levels rise, it binds to mineralocorticoid receptors in the principal cells, leading to increased synthesis of sodium channels and sodium-potassium ATPase pumps. The sodium channels on the luminal side facilitate increased sodium reabsorption from the tubular lumen into the cell. Simultaneously, the sodium-potassium ATPase pumps on the basolateral membrane pump sodium out of the cell into the bloodstream while importing potassium into the cell. The resulting increase in intracellular potassium concentration drives the secretion of potassium ions (K⁺) from the cell into the tubular lumen. Thus, under the influence of aldosterone, there is increased sodium reabsorption and potassium secretion.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 387.","responses":[{"text":"H⁺","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Na⁺","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cl⁻","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ca⁺","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"K⁺","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16025,"text":"Which of the following nerves supplies the sensory innervation to the bladder?","explanation":"The bladder receives its sensory innervation primarily through the pelvic nerve. The pelvic nerve, also known as the parasympathetic pelvic splanchnic nerve, carries both sensory and parasympathetic motor fibers. Sensory fibers transmit sensations of bladder fullness and the urge to void to the central nervous system. These fibers originate from the vesical plexus around the bladder and ascend with the parasympathetic fibers to the sacral spinal cord segments, primarily S2 to S4. It's crucial for the micturition reflex, allowing the brain to perceive when the bladder is full. The pudendal nerve mainly supplies the external urethral and anal sphincters. The hypogastric nerve carries sympathetic fibers. While the sacral nerves play a role in the motor aspect of bladder function, the term \"sacral nerve\" is broad and does not specifically denote the sensory innervation to the bladder.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 326.","responses":[{"text":"Sacral nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pelvic nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pudendal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypogastric nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pelvic splanchnic nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16026,"text":"Which of the following is the most commonly used test to assess renal function?","explanation":"Creatinine clearance is the most commonly used test to assess renal function in clinical practice. Creatinine is a waste product formed from the metabolism of creatine in muscle and is excreted unchanged by the kidneys. Unlike urea or uric acid, which can be affected by various factors, creatinine is produced at a steady rate and its serum levels provide a reliable indication of renal function. \r\n\r\nCreatinine clearance measures the volume of blood cleared of creatinine per unit of time and provides an estimate of the glomerular filtration rate (GFR), which is a vital parameter to assess kidney function. While inulin clearance is theoretically the gold standard for measuring GFR, it is not routinely used due to the practical difficulties in administering inulin and collecting timed urine samples.","reference":"(1) Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 360, 361.\r\n\r\n(2) Gounden V, Bhatt H, Jialal I. Renal function tests. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed June 1, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK507821/","responses":[{"text":"Para-aminohippuric acid clearance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Uric acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inulin clearance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Creatinine clearance","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16027,"text":"Which of the following structures is most likely to be damaged during the surgical approach of kidneys around the 11th or 12th rib?","explanation":"The kidneys are retroperitoneal organs situated against the posterior abdominal wall. During a surgical approach to the kidneys, typically around the 11th or 12th rib, the structure at the highest risk of being inadvertently damaged is the pleura, specifically the posterior part of the diaphragmatic pleura. The pleura is a thin serous membrane that covers the lungs and lines the inside of the chest cavity. The lower edges of the parietal pleura extend slightly below the level of the 12th rib posteriorly. A surgical incision or approach at this level carries a risk of accidentally puncturing the pleura, which can lead to a pneumothorax (presence of air in the pleural cavity) if the lung is also damaged.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 340.","responses":[{"text":"Lesser sac of peritoneal cavity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diaphragm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pleura","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lungs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pericardium","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16028,"text":"Which of the following cells associated with the glomerular capillaries are involved in phagocytosis of macromolecules, adjusting filtration rate, mediating immune response in a glomerulus, and providing structural support?","explanation":"Mesangial cells are specialized cells located in the renal glomerulus. These cells have multiple roles in the maintenance and function of the glomerular filtration barrier:\r\n\r\n1. **Phagocytosis of Macromolecules**: Mesangial cells can phagocytose trapped macromolecules and immune complexes that might otherwise obstruct the glomerular capillaries.\r\n\r\n2. **Adjusting Filtration Rate**: These cells can contract and relax, thereby regulating the surface area of the glomerular capillaries available for filtration.\r\n\r\n3. **Mediating Immune Response**: Mesangial cells can produce cytokines and take part in immune reactions, especially in certain glomerular diseases.\r\n\r\n4. **Providing Structural Support**: They offer structural support to the glomerular capillaries and maintain the integrity of the glomerular tuft.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 400.","responses":[{"text":"Podocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Kupffer cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endothelial cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mesangial cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Principal cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16029,"text":"The decrease in sodium chloride (NaCl) concentration in the glomerular filtrate, when sensed by the macula densa is most likely to result in which of the following responses?","explanation":"The macula densa is a specialized region in the distal convoluted tubule that senses changes in the concentration of sodium chloride (NaCl) in the glomerular filtrate. A decrease in NaCl concentration at the macula densa indicates reduced filtrate flow or reduced salt delivery, which might be due to decreased renal perfusion or glomerular filtration rate (GFR).\r\n\r\nIn response to decreased NaCl concentration, the macula densa signals the adjacent juxtaglomerular cells (found in the walls of the afferent arterioles) to release renin. Renin then catalyzes the conversion of angiotensinogen to angiotensin I, eventually leading to the formation of angiotensin II. Angiotensin II induces vasoconstriction, increases aldosterone release, and ultimately helps to raise blood pressure and restore GFR and NaCl delivery.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 340.","responses":[{"text":"Increased release of renin from juxtaglomerular cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Dilation of efferent arterioles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Contraction of afferent arterioles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibition of renin release from juxtaglomerular cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Contraction of mesangial cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16055,"text":"A histopathologist observes a slide of the wall of the urinary bladder with three distinct layers the mucosa, muscularis, and serosa. Which of the following parts of the bladder is under observation?","explanation":"The urinary bladder is characterized by its distinctive histological layers, including the mucosa (with transitional epithelium), muscularis, and either a serosa or adventitia, depending on its location. The superior surface (or dome) of the bladder is covered by the peritoneum and hence has a serosa. This differentiates the superior surface from other parts of the bladder.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, other surfaces like the inferolateral surface, trigone, neck, and fundus, which are not covered by the peritoneum, have an adventitia instead of a serosa. The presence of a serosa suggests that the observed part is in direct contact with the peritoneal cavity.","reference":"Laiq Hussain Siddiqui. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 218.","responses":[{"text":"Superior surface","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Trigone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferolateral surface","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neck","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fundus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16056,"text":"Which of the following conditions results in efflux of potassium ions from the cell?","explanation":"In metabolic acidosis, there's an accumulation of H+ ions (protons) inside cells. To buffer or neutralize this increased intracellular acid concentration, cells will take in more H+ ions. To maintain electrical neutrality, potassium (K+) ions move out of the cell in exchange for the H+ ions moving into the cell. This leads to hyperkalemia, an elevated level of potassium in the extracellular fluid.\r\n\r\nFactors such as hyperaldosteronism, increased insulin levels, and β-adrenergic stimulation have the opposite effect – they promote the uptake of potassium into cells, which decreases extracellular potassium levels. Metabolic alkalosis, on the other hand, generally causes hypokalemia due to increased cellular uptake of potassium and increased renal excretion, but it does not cause potassium to efflux from cells like metabolic acidosis does.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 384.","responses":[{"text":"Increased Insulin level","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metabolic acidosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"β-adrenergic stimulation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metabolic alkalosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperaldosteronism","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16057,"text":"Aspartate enters the Krebs cycle as which of the following compounds?","explanation":"Aspartate can be deaminated to form oxaloacetate in a transaminase reaction, where the amino group is transferred to α-ketoglutarate to form glutamate. This conversion is facilitated by the enzyme aspartate aminotransferase (AST). \r\n\r\nOxaloacetate is one of the key intermediates in the Krebs (citric acid) cycle. It can condense with acetyl-CoA to initiate the cycle, producing citrate in the process, catalyzed by the enzyme citrate synthase.","reference":"(1) Murray RK, Victor WR, Bender D, Kathleen MB, Weil PA, Kennelly PJ. Harper’s Illustrated Biochemistry. 28th ed. McGraw-Hill Professional; 2009: 133.\r\n(2) Dow Lecture Slides. GIT and Liver Module. Subject: Biochemistry. Topic: TCA cycle, Sub-topic: Influx of TCA cycle intermediates.","responses":[{"text":"α-ketoglutarate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Succinyl CoA","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Citrate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fumarate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxaloacetate","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16058,"text":"The pain due to a ureteric calculi can extend from the loin to the groin. This area is supplied by which of the following spinal segments?","explanation":"The pain resulting from a ureteric calculus, commonly referred to as renal colic, arises as the stone moves down the ureter. This pain is visceral in nature and is typically referred to the dermatomes corresponding to the innervation of the ureter.\r\n\r\nThe ureter receives its primary sensory innervation from the renal and aortic plexuses. This innervation mainly arises from **T11 to L2** spinal segments. The referred pain, therefore, often starts in the flank or loin (corresponding to the upper ureter) and moves anteroinferiorly towards the groin (corresponding to the lower ureter and ureterovesical junction).\r\n\r\nIn addition to this, the testicles in males and the labia majora in females might also be sites of referred pain, a phenomenon attributed to the shared sensory innervation from T10 to T11.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 526.","responses":[{"text":"T12 to L3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"S1 to S3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T11 to L2","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"L1 and L2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"L1 to L3","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16103,"text":"Which of the following parts of the male urethra is lined by pseudostratified columnar epithelium?","explanation":"The male urethra consists of distinct segments, each with its specific epithelial lining:\r\n \r\n1. **Prostatic urethra**: This segment traverses the prostate gland and is predominantly lined by urothelium.\r\n  \r\n2. **Membranous urethra**: A shorter portion, the membranous urethra, courses through the external sphincter made of striated muscle. It is uniquely lined by a combination of **stratified columnar** and **pseudostratified columnar epithelium**. \r\n\r\n3. **Spongy urethra**: The longest segment of the male urethra, the spongy urethra, is enveloped within the erectile tissue of the penis. It also possesses a lining of stratified columnar and pseudostratified columnar epithelium, transitioning to stratified squamous epithelium towards its distal end.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 410.","responses":[{"text":"Bulbar urethra","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urethral meatus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prostatic urethra","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Membranous urethra","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Navicular fossa","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

